rnal friction of travelling in Svalbard during the fertile height of the Arctic summer. Blending travelogue and poetic meditation on place, Jenna Butler draws readers to the beauty and power of threatened landscapes, asking why some stories in recorded history are privileged while others speak only from beneath the surface.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian poetry. 0aClimatic changeszArctic regions. 0aFeminism. 0aOcean travelvPoetry. 0aOcean travel. 7aTravel / Essays & Travelogues.2bisacsh  aThe North / Environment / Travel / Women's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978177212423140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781772124231423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781772124231/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles